{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6ce6babd-c713-45bb-8033-ca25a4451907","content":"Here are the pod spec changes you need:\n\n**Environment variables** on your container:\n\n```yaml\nenv:\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump\n    value: \"1\"\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType\n    value: \"2\"                          # WithHeap (1=Normal, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName\n    value: \"/dumps/crash_%t_%p.dmp\"     # %t=timestamp, %p=PID\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath\n    value: \"/opt/tools/createdump\"      # your custom path\n```\n\n**Volume mount + volume** for persisting dumps:\n\n```yaml\ncontainers:\n  - name: my-app\n    # ... existing config ...\n    volumeMounts:\n      - name: crash-dumps\n        mountPath: /dumps\nvolumes:\n  - name: crash-dumps\n    emptyDir:\n      sizeLimit: 2Gi          # adjust to expected dump size\n```\n\n**Key notes:**\n\n- **`emptyDir`** is fine for short-term collection; swap to a **PVC** or **hostPath** if you need dumps to survive pod restarts.\n- `MiniDumpType=2` (WithHeap) is usually the best balance for NativeAOT — it includes the managed heap but not full memory. Use `4` (Full) only if you need native memory analysis.\n- Ensure your container runs with `SYS_PTRACE` capability if createdump fails with permission errors:\n\n```yaml\nsecurityContext:\n  capabilities:\n    add: [\"SYS_PTRACE\"]\n```\n\n- To ship dumps out, consider adding a **sidecar** that watches `/dumps` and uploads to blob storage, or use a `preStop` hook.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c131daee-403b-447f-b2f2-8c6862f30a2b","outputTokens":452,"requestId":"204C:913B3:720965:84B32D:69F011F1"},"id":"e42894a9-06ae-40ae-ae87-c0a60963150f","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:48:45.059Z","parentId":"57b7ecbc-c2df-418e-8511-409b50aa49f4"}
